# Gold Layer — Dimensions, Facts & Data Marts

Build the complete Gold/Platinum layer for the F1 Data Warehouse: 6 dimension tables, 4 fact tables, and 8 data mart tables.

## Current State

The **staging** and **intermediate** layers are complete:

| Layer | Models | Status |
|---|---|---|
| Staging (Kaggle) | 12 models (`stg_kaggle_*`) | ✅ Done |
| Staging (Jolpica) | 5 models (`stg_jolpica_*`) | ✅ Done |
| Staging (OpenF1) | 4 models (`stg_openf1_*`) | ✅ Done |
| Intermediate | 9 models (`int_*`) — bridges, unified tables, enriched | ✅ Done |
| **Gold / Marts** | **0 models** | 🔴 Not started |

The intermediate layer already solved identity fragmentation (bridge tables), timeline gaps (unified tables), and grain mismatches (EOY standings). The gold layer reads almost exclusively from intermediate models.

---

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Pragmatic Key Strategy**: The original star schema design calls for BIGINT surrogate keys on all dimensions (e.g., `driver_key`, `race_key`). Since the intermediate layer already resolved all identity conflicts to canonical Kaggle integer IDs (`driver_id`, `race_id`, `constructor_id`, `circuit_id`), I propose **keeping natural integer keys** instead of adding a surrogate key layer. This avoids unnecessary complexity — the bridge tables already act as our key resolver. The column will still be called `driver_key` etc. for naming consistency, but its value will be the resolved integer.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **SCD Type 2 on `dim_constructor`**: The design doc calls for SCD2 tracking of constructor name changes (e.g., Benetton → Renault → Lotus → Alpine). However, the Kaggle source treats each team name as a **separate `constructor_id`** (Benetton = 1, Renault = 4, etc.), not as versions of the same entity. Implementing true SCD2 would require a manually curated mapping of team lineages that doesn't exist in any source. I'll add a `parent_team` column to `dim_constructor` and hardcode the known lineages (5-6 entries), but won't implement full SCD2 with `valid_from`/`valid_to` — it adds complexity with no practical benefit given the source data structure.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **`dim_date` — Skip?**: The design doc includes a full calendar dimension. Since every fact already has `season_year` as a partition column and we have `race_date` in `dim_race`, a separate date dimension adds ~28K rows for zero dashboard value. I propose skipping `dim_date` entirely.

## Open Questions

> [!NOTE]
> **`mart_head_to_head` scope**: The star schema defines this as 1 row per `(driver_a, driver_b, season)` — only for **teammates**. That's what the mock dashboard's "Compare" tab shows. Should we also support cross-team comparisons (Hamilton vs Schumacher), or keep it teammate-only? I'll implement **teammate-only** for now (this is what the data naturally supports), and the dashboard's cross-team compare can query `mart_driver_career` directly.

> [!NOTE]
> **`mart_records` format**: The design doc has `mart_records` with one row per record category (e.g., "Most Wins", "Most Poles"). This is a denormalized metadata table. Should I hardcode the record categories or dynamically compute them from the data? I'll go with **dynamic computation** — more maintainable as records change.

